            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "size": 1682,
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_01YbPv5Gu7Kmx9CDYRUuWTSa\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Great question! **Descriptions** are the supporting text lines that appear below your headlines in Google Ads.\\n\\nHere's what you need to know about them:\\n\\n**Key Details:**\\n- **Length limit:** Up to 70 characters each (strict Google limit)\\n- **Placement:** They appear below your headlines in search results\\n- **How many show:** Google typically displays up to 2 description lines in a single ad\\n- **Purpose:** They give you space to explain benefits, features, and calls to action\\n\\n**What makes them effective:**\\n- They expand on the value proposition introduced in your headlines\\n- They should include a clear call-to-action (like \\\"Call now,\\\" \\\"Get a quote,\\\" or \\\"Learn more\\\")\\n- They can highlight social proof, special offers, or specific benefits\\n- They work together with your headlines to convince someone to click your ad\\n\\nThink of it this way: Your **headlines** grab attention, and your **descriptions** convince people to take action by explaining *why* they should click.\\n\\nFor your scheduling tool, descriptions might highlight things like \\\"Cut meeting coordination time by 80%\\\" or \\\"Works across all time zones—no more scheduling chaos.\\\"\\n\\nWould you like me to generate some headlines and descriptions for your scheduling tool campaign?\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":2587,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":272,\"service_tier\":\"standard\"}}"
